  "prompt": "Can you become an Army Sniper while in the Army Reserves?",
  "response": "While it is possible to become a sniper in the Army Reserves, it is less common and more challenging compared to Active Duty. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Typically, most Army Sniper opportunities are in Active Duty units, particularly in Infantry and Special Forces.\n\n2. Reserve units do have some sniper positions, but they are limited and competitive.\n\n3. To become a sniper in the Reserves, you would need to:\n- Meet the initial qualifications\n- Complete Basic Combat Training\n- Attend Advanced Individual Training (AIT)\n- Be selected for and pass the Sniper School\n- Have your unit support and have an available sniper position\n\n4. You might need to transfer to a specific Reserve unit that has a sniper role available.\n\n5. The Army's Sniper School (located at Fort Benning, Georgia) is primarily geared towards Active Duty soldiers.\n\nWhile not impossible, becoming a Reserve sniper requires extra effort, motivation, and potentially some flexibility in your unit assignment. Consulting with a Reserve recruiter can provide the most current and specific guidance for your situation.",
